cybermission is designed for adults and uses a navy blue cyber-world and military-style background to create a serious and immersive atmosphere.
the game includes icons such as trophies, badges, locks, warning signs, and risk-level indicators, which strenghthen the cybersecurity theme.
Its hacker and military-inspired environment attracts users, while interactive levels and time limits help maintain attention by creating urgency and excitement.
The feedback system rewards players with rankings and medals such as gold, silver, and bronze, while also explaining mistakes made during gameplay.
From this example, we plan to apply a cyber-military theme in our own design.

Prodigy Education mainly targets adults and uses bright colours such as blue, green, and purple to create an engaging and fantasy-like environment.
The game features visual icons including magic stars, trophies, and other symbols that reduce the need for long text explanations. 
Its fantasy adventure style helps hold users’ attention, and the use of visual symbols makes the experience more interactive and easier to follow. 
The reward system provides immediate feedback during battles, where correct answers help players progress and wrong answers explain mistakes clearly. 
From this game, we will apply the use of visual symbols and interactive feedback.

CyberEdu is aimed at university students and uses dark blue colours with neon blue and green highlights alongside a digital city background.
The interface includes cybersecurity-related icons such as shields, padlocks, warning triangles, laptops, and email symbols.
The game keeps users engaged through multiple levels, story progression, and interactive problem-solving activities.
It also provides security-warning feedback to guide users and improve learning. 
From this example, we plan to use high-contrast colours and interactive progression features in our design.
